# Commit messages

When drafting or suggesting git commit messages, use this structure (not a single vague line).

## Structure

1. **Title** — One line: what was added or changed, active voice, no period.
2. **Body** — Short paragraphs (not bullet lists), grouped by area (backend/API, frontend, infra, etc.).
3. **Footer** — Verification when relevant: tests, typecheck, build, manual checks.

## Example

```
Add batch verification (concurrent) and results dashboard

Add a /verify/batch endpoint that verifies many COLA records concurrently
(bounded by a semaphore) and isolates per-record failures, plus a frontend
Batch tab: multi-file upload, summary chips with status filtering, a sortable
results table, per-row drill-in reusing the report, and CSV export.

46 backend tests green; frontend typechecks. Browser-verified on 3 real
records (all PASS, processed in parallel).
```

## Example (this project)

```
Add Candidate Screen async video interview platform

Ship a Next.js 15 app with marketing pages, email auth, a recruiter console,
and a candidate recording flow backed by Postgres and Prisma.

Recruiter console: dashboard, interviews list/build, role-scoped candidates
index and pipeline, video review with scorecard, analytics, settings, and
billing. Candidate experience: invite link flow with camera/mic setup,
think-time countdown, recording, per-question review, and submission.

Includes session auth, workspace model, mock-data dev bypass for local UI
preview, and design-handoff-aligned recruiter UI components.

Production build and TypeScript check pass; .env and design handoff excluded
via .gitignore.
```

## Rules

- Title states the **user-visible outcome** or feature, not "update files" or "fix stuff".
- Body explains **why** and **what areas** changed; mention important endpoints, routes, or UX flows.
- Do not list every file path in the message.
- For `git commit -m`, use multiple `-m` flags for title and body paragraphs when the shell does not support heredocs.
